04738nam a22007335i 9780292742116DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212012txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2012013006  a97802927421167 a10.7560/7286912doi  a(DE-B1597)588199  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aTS806.T4bT393 2012 4aTS806.T4 ǂb T39 2012eb 7aANT0170002bisacsh04a338.476841091 aTaylor, Lonn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTexas Furniture, Volume One :bThe Cabinetmakers and Their Work, 1840-1880, Revised edition /cLonn Taylor, David B. Warren. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2012  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tMid-Nineteenth-Century Texas: The Coast and the Hinterland -- tCabinetmaking in the Hinterland -- tFurniture of the Frontier: The Surviving Evidence -- t1. Beds, cribs, and cradles -- t2. Wardrobes -- t3. Chests of drawers -- t4. Chairs and stools -- t5. Sofas, settees, Benches, and day Beds -- t6. Tables and stands -- t7. Desks -- t8. Cupboards -- t9. Safes -- tA Checklist of Texas Cabinetmakers -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe art of furniture making flourished in Texas during the mid-nineteenth century. To document this rich heritage of locally made furniture, Miss Ima Hogg, the well-known philanthropist and collector of American decorative arts, enlisted Lonn Taylor and David B. Warren to research early Texas Furniture and its makers. They spent more than a decade working with museums and private collectors throughout the state to examine and photograph representative examples. They also combed census records, newspapers, and archives for information about cabinetmakers. These efforts resulted in the 1975 publication of Texas Furniture, which quickly became the authoritative reference on this subject. Now updated with an expanded Index of Texas Cabinetmakers that includes information that has come to light since the original publication and corrects errors, Texas Furniture presents a catalog of more than two hundred pieces of furniture, each superbly photographed and accompanied by detailed descriptions of the piece’s maker, date, materials, measurements, history, and owner, as well as an analysis by the authors. The book also includes chapters on the material culture of nineteenth-century Texas and on the tools and techniques of nineteenth-century Texas cabinetmakers, with a special emphasis on the German immigrant cabinetmakers of the Hill Country and Central Texas. The index of Texas cabinetmakers contains biographical information on approximately nine hundred men who made furniture in Texas, and appendices list information on the state’s largest cabinet shops taken from the United States census records.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aFurniture -- Texas. 0aFurniture industry and trade -- Texas -- History. 0aFurniture industry and tradezTexasxHistory. 0aFurniturezTexas. 7aANTIQUES & COLLECTIBLES / Furniture.2bisacsh1 aHogg, Ima, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHogg, Ima.1 aWarren, David B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72869140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292742116423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292742116/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1